Data Wrangling

Let’s start with the map after we join the assaults to fishnet. (code blocks are not shown because they are the same as HW instructions)

In order to build a better version of the given model, I downloaded other features from Chicago’s data portal that are possibly related to crime presence, including 311 reports of alley lights-out, sanitation complaints, grafitti removal requests, rodent baiting requests, park locations, and police station locations, etc.

As for the existing features, I re-engineered several of them, including:

  • Combine the data of Street Lights-out Complaints with Alley Lights-out Complaints into one
  • instead of the count of abandoned buildings, use the distance to 5 nearest abandoned buildings as predictor
  • instead of the count of liquor retail, use the distance to 3 nearest liquor stores as predictor
  • instead of nearest neighbor distance, use the count of schools in each fishnet as predictor
  • extract from the business license dataset another type of liquor-related business “late hour” and their locations

In addition, several new features are added:

  • the count of service requests complaining sanitation code violation
  • the count of service requests of rodent baiting (indicative of the presence of rats)
  • the distance to five nearest parks’ centroids
  • the distance to the nearest police station
  • the distance to five nearest parks’ centroid

Below is the code for collecting and wrangling these independent variables.

Then join every set of event points to the fishnet.

allVars.sf <-
  rbind(lightsOut,school,sanitationComplaints,
        rodentBaiting,GraffitiRemoval)

vars_net <-
  st_join(allVars.sf, fishnet, join=st_within) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  group_by(uniqueID,Legend) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  full_join(fishnet) %>%
  spread(Legend,count, fill=0) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  na.omit()

Then we will move on to measure average nearest neighbor distance.
First step is to create a function.

Now let’s calculate the average distance of each fishnet’s centroid to the nearest police station.

nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {

  nn <-
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist

  output <-
    as.data.frame(nn) %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
    gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    group_by(thisPoint) %>%
    summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    dplyr::select(-thisPoint)

  return(output)
}
policeStation <-
  read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/Public-Safety/Police-Stations/z8bn-74gv") %>%
  dplyr::select(LATITUDE,LONGITUDE, Y = LATITUDE, X = LONGITUDE) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("X", "Y"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant") %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  st_transform(st_crs(fishnet))

vars_net.xy <-
  st_centroid(vars_net) %>%
  cbind(.,st_coordinates(st_centroid(vars_net))) %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  dplyr::select(X,Y) %>%
  as.matrix()

police.xy <-
  policeStation %>%
  cbind(.,st_coordinates(st_centroid(policeStation)))  %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  dplyr::select(X,Y) %>%
  as.matrix()

distPolice <- as.data.frame(nn_function(vars_net.xy,police.xy,1))

vars_net <-
  cbind(as.data.frame(vars_net),distPolice) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  rename(PoliceStadis=pointDistance)

The feature “distance to loop” in the original model is kept in this model as a feature to indicate the proximaty to commercial center.

Exploratory anlaysis

To start I am going to do some exploratory mapping of independent variables.

The plot of nearest neighbor distance to schools showed in class displayed very small variation across the city. So I think that maybe, compared to each cell’s general distance to nearby schools, the presence and the exact number of schools in the cell is more related to the assualts happened in that area. The count of schools by fishnet unit is presented below. In this way the variation is much easier to be observed.

And here are the mapping of the average nearest neighbor distance of police station and late hour business.

Estimate models

Now we move on to the regression model. The code block below builds our regression model and returns the result summary.

reg <- glm(countAssaults ~ ., family = "poisson",
           data= final_net %>%
             as.data.frame %>%
             dplyr::select(countAssaults,
                           AbandonBuildingdis,
                           Graffiti_removal,
                           School,
                           Lights_Out,
                           Rodent_complaints,
                           Sanitation_complaints,
                           PoliceStadis,
                           Liquordistance,
                           Parkdistance,
                           lateHourdis,
                           loopDistance
             ))
summary(reg)

As shown in the results, all the variable coefficients are statistically significant. We then standardize the coefficients to put them on the same scale. As can be seen from the bar chart below, the nearest neighbor distance to abandoned buildings and liquor stores have the largest effects on assaults presence.

standardized <- as.data.frame(lm.beta(reg))
standardized$variable <- row.names(standardized)
colnames(standardized)[1] <- "std_coefficient"

standardized$absCoef <- abs(standardized$std_coefficient)

ggplot(standardized, aes(x=reorder(variable,-absCoef), y=absCoef, fill=variable)) +

Goodness of fit

Based on the model prediction results we can calculate the MAE(Mean Absolute Error) and MAPE(Mean Absolute Percentage Error). Because there are many 0 value in assualt count it is a little wierd to compute MAPE, as I remove many infinite values from the dataset.
For this model the MAE is 4.412, which is slightly better than the original model, and MAPE is 1.003.

final_net <-
  cbind(final_net,reg$fitted.values) %>%
  rename(predictedValue = reg.fitted.values) %>%
  mutate(absError = abs(countAssaults - predictedValue)) %>%
  mutate(pctabsError = abs(countAssaults - predictedValue)/countAssaults)

is.na(final_net$pctabsError) <- sapply(final_net$pctabsError, is.infinite)

MAE <-  mean(final_net$absError)
MAPE <-  mean(na.omit(final_net$pctabsError))

Then let’s see how the absolute error distributes across the city based on the unit of fishnet cell.

We will also plot a map showing the mean absolute error by neighborhood. As can be observed from below, the general goodness of fit is not too bad, and the absolute error goes higher in areas adjacent to Chicago’s Central Business District. That probably makes sense as the crime pattern becomes more unpredictable due to high density of population and activities.

neighborhood_error <-
  final_net %>%
  st_transform(st_crs(neighborhoods)) %>%
  aggregate(., neighborhoods, mean) %>%
  dplyr::select(predictedValue,absError,pctabsError )


ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data=neighborhood_error, aes(fill=absError)) +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  labs(title= "Residuals by Neighborhood") +
  mapTheme()

Then we move on to create the kernel density vs. risk prediction plot. According to the plot, the areas that our model predict as high risk (70%~100%) hold larger percentage of observed assualts than the high risk area predicted by kernel density. Also, in the areas that are predicted as low risk (1%~49%) by our model, there are smaller percentage of actual assualts that fall inside compared to the ones predicted by kernel density. This indicates that our model is doing a better job than kernel density.

Interpretation

Given the use case, the model is comparatively successful. According to the maps, the high risk areas this model predicts are almost the same as the areas with high density of assualt presence in reality. Based on its prediction, the cops may assign more resources to the high-risk areas to prevent some potential assualts from happening.

Nevertheless, this model might be biased. Although generally it predicts regional crime risk with high accuracy, we can find a discernable pattern in the mapping of residuals by neighborhood - the areas that are predicted to have high risk of assualts yield bigger error in the prediction results, which means that high risk areas tend to be either over-predict or under-predict.
